\pard\plain \fi720\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The moment was perfect.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Lorba Bargu had her nice, cozy rocking chair she\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d built out of a bent and sanded gabbu tree she grew from a seed. She had her nice, heavy blue blanket that her loving husband Kam had knit out of the softest wool. The silver sky was pleasant, with the rain tap-tapping on the clay-shingles of her master\u8217\'92s wagon house, which was better described as a sheltered porch adjoining her master\u8217\'92s western wall. It was not a grand shelter, though it offered a grand view, advantaged, as it was, at the top of Meskalim's central hill looking west, with the sprawling mud-city spread out below and the foggy, Shalbrum Sea boiling beyond it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The moment\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s only discordant note was her blistered heels, for she was still wearing in the stiff leather boots made two days before by her son, who was a cobbler\u8217\'92s apprentice. This slight pain was a beauty mark, an ugliness which when juxtaposed against perfection enhanced it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Yes, the moment was perfect.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Almost perfect.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Unfortunately, her wagon\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s bed was full-up with the half-dead bodies of artists. She knew they were artists, because when her master carried them out of the great house they had paint on their fingers and clothes, usually black paint. And she knew they were only half-dead instead of full-dead, because after killing them, her master brought them out to her wagon house to administer a rainbow potion which, he claimed, \u8216\'91stabilized the Spark\u8217\'92. Her master kept this potion hidden in a false drawer in her workbench. Lorba never touched this hidden treasure. She wanted nothing to do with it. She only ever watched when her master would force a few drops of that shimmering liquid down into the corpse\u8217\'92s mouth, and she didn\u8217\'92t help when he sat the the poor wretches up and shook them to make sure the liquid was running fast down into the stomach. To her, this habit of her master\u8217\'92s was an eccentricity she could forgive for the sake of the job, for the sake of these moments where she could sit high up, rock back-and-forth, and feel comfortable, secure, even delight at how her life had turned out.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93You think his Spark has faded?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Salavan shook his fat head. He nodded towards the wagon and said, \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Stuff him in with the others.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1
